## Methodology (from Jimenez et al. 2022, arXiv:2203.14247)

### Physical Model

Three neutrino mass eigenstates (mв‚Ѓ, mв‚‚, mв‚ѓ). Two orderings:
- NH: mв‚Ѓ в‰¤ mв‚‚ в‰¤ mв‚ѓ в†’ lightest is mв‚Ѓ, intermediate mв‚‚, heaviest mв‚ѓ
- IH: mв‚ѓ в‰¤ mв‚Ѓ в‰¤ mв‚‚ в†’ lightest is mв‚ѓ, intermediate mв‚Ѓ, heaviest mв‚‚

Parameterize as (mL, mM, mH) = (lightest, middle, heaviest). Then:

For NH: mв‚‚ = sqrt(mв‚ЃВІ + О”mВІв‚‚в‚Ѓ), mв‚ѓ = sqrt(mв‚ЃВІ + О”mВІв‚ѓв‚Ѓ)
For IH: mв‚Ѓ = sqrt(mв‚ѓВІ + |О”mВІв‚ѓв‚‚| - О”mВІв‚‚в‚Ѓ), mв‚‚ = sqrt(mв‚ѓВІ + |О”mВІв‚ѓв‚‚|)
Sum: ОЈ = mL + mM + mH

The cosmological likelihood depends only on ОЈ.
The oscillation likelihood depends on О”mВІв‚‚в‚Ѓ and О”mВІв‚ѓв„“.

### Bayesian Evidence

For each ordering M в€€ {NH, IH}:

P(D | M) = в€« P(D_cosmo | ОЈ) P(D_osc | mв‚Ѓ, mв‚‚, mв‚ѓ) P(mв‚Ѓ, mв‚‚, mв‚ѓ | M) dmв‚Ѓ dmв‚‚ dmв‚ѓ

Bayes factor: K = P(D | NH) / P(D | IH)

The evidence ratio K is the primary output. On the Jeffreys scale:
- K > 3.2: "substantial" evidence
- K > 10: "strong" evidence
- K > 100: "decisive" evidence

### Prior 1: SJPV (Hierarchical Logarithmic вЂ” Jimenez et al.)

The prior on each individual mass before oscillation data is log-normal:
  P(log mбµў | Ој, Пѓ) ~ N(log Ој, Пѓ)

with hyperpriors (uniform in log space):
  ПЂ(log Ој) ~ U(log(5Г—10вЃ»вЃґ eV), log(0.3 eV))
  ПЂ(log Пѓ) ~ U(log(5Г—10вЃ»Ві), log(20))

The three masses are exchangeable (drawn from the same common distribution), reflecting the belief that all three masses share a common generation mechanism. The total prior marginalizes over Ој and Пѓ.

The evidence integral becomes 5-dimensional: (mв‚Ѓ or mL, Ој, Пѓ) plus constraints from oscillations.

Implementation: numerical integration or MCMC over (mL, Ој, Пѓ) with the oscillation data folded in.

### Prior 2: HS (Objective Bayesian / Jeffreys-Fisher вЂ” Simpson et al.)

Reference prior derived from Fisher information of the oscillation likelihood:
  P(mL, mM, mH) в€ќ J(mL, mM, mH) = 4(mLВ·mM + mLВ·mH + mMВ·mH)

This is the Jacobian of the transformation from natural oscillation parameters (П†=О”mВІв‚‚в‚Ѓ, П€=О”mВІв‚ѓв„“, ОЈ) to individual masses.

Upper truncation at ОЈmax = 1.5 eV (improper prior regularization).

### Cosmological Likelihood Model

From the DESI DR2 chain, extract the marginalized 1D posterior P(ОЈmОЅ | DESI+CMB). For the Bayesian evidence calculation, treat this as the likelihood: P(D_cosmo | ОЈ).

Two representations:
1. Direct: use kernel density estimate (KDE) of chain samples for P(ОЈ | data)
2. Gaussian approximation: P(ОЈ | data) в€ќ exp(в€’(ОЈ в€’ Ојв‚Ђ)ВІ/(2ПѓВІ)) Г— Оё(ОЈ) where Оё is Heaviside

For the Gaussian approximation, fit to the chain posterior: find Ојв‚Ђ and Пѓ such that 95th percentile matches published limit. Also use the profile likelihood values (Ојв‚Ђ = в€’0.036 eV, Пѓ = 0.043 eV) for Feldman-Cousins comparison.

### Double-Beta Decay Implications (Majorana Neutrinos)

Effective Majorana mass:
  mОІОІ = |ОЈбµў Uв‚‘бµўВІ mбµў| where U is PMNS matrix

For the theoretical upper limit of the half-life of neutrinoless double-beta decay:
  T^(0ОЅОІОІ)_{1/2} в€ќ 1/mОІОІВІ

Using the posterior on (mв‚Ѓ, mв‚‚, mв‚ѓ) from the NH analysis, compute the posterior on mОІОІ and compare to IH case. Show the allowed ranges of mОІОІ for NH vs IH given DESI DR2 + oscillation constraints. PMNS parameters from NuFIT 6.0.

